##Ge Yulu, Wuhan Native: I bought a Kayak and plan to row into Beijing

Micro-signal GQREPORT

Function introduction, record the rise and fall of the characters and changes in the value of the Times. Complete, true, in-depth, accurate non-fiction stories, sent to you every week.

In October, Ge Yulu, a performance artist who once named an unnamed road in Baiziwan after himself, began a new city related project: Sending a letter across town in the wind. After an 8-day, 67-hour walk, he used an electric fan and blower to blow a love letter, with only a head and sign, from Yanjiao to Beijing and into the hands of his girlfriend.
"It's a kind of earthy romance only found in Beijing, " said Ge Yulu. As a Wuhan native, one of his first impressions after coming to Beijing was that the wind in Beijing was really strong. "I believe that many people have the same fate as me, just like the wind I make myself. With just a little bit of force, any breeze from Beijing can easily blow me back. So every time there is a strong wind in Beijing, I have to wait and wait for the chance to blow into the city again."
On Valentine's Day this year, a video recording the performance art went viral. At the time, he was isolated from his girlfriend, who was also from Wuhan, in a rented house in Yanjiao. Going out once in a while to buy shrimp for my girlfriend, "people from other parts of the country are afraid to marry people from Wuhan, because Wuhan girls have bad tempers and are very aggressive. Many families in Wuhan are decided by women, and my girlfriend often stresses that we are not equal, " Ge said.
Yanjiao is separated from Beijing by a river, but it is not the river but the checkpoint on the river that separates them. Checkpoints play an extremely important role in the lives of Yanjiao people.
One day in late February, Ge Yulu was told that, as a Wuhan native whose ID card began with 42, he would have to hand in his residence card and would not be allowed to enter the community again, six months after his last visit to Wuhan. At the same time, he had bought a ticket to Thailand, with this 42 ID card, through the Beijing checkpoint.
A few days ago, I had a chat with Ge Yulu, who was already in Bangkok. He told me the story of a man from Wuhan who had come to Beijing twice.

In October, Ge Yulu, a performance artist who once named an unnamed road in Baiziwan after himself, began a new city related project: Sending a letter across town in the wind. After an 8-day, 67-hour walk, he used an electric fan and blower to blow a love letter, with only a head and sign, from Yanjiao to Beijing and into the hands of his girlfriend.

"It's a kind of earthy romance only found in Beijing, " said Ge Yulu. As a Wuhan native, one of his first impressions after coming to Beijing was that the wind in Beijing was really strong. "I believe that many people have the same fate as me, just like the wind I make myself. With just a little bit of force, any breeze from Beijing can easily blow me back. So every time there is a strong wind in Beijing, I have to wait and wait for the chance to blow into the city again."

On Valentine's Day this year, a video recording the performance art went viral. At the time, he was isolated from his girlfriend, who was also from Wuhan, in a rented house in Yanjiao. Going out once in a while to buy shrimp for my girlfriend, "people from other parts of the country are afraid to marry people from Wuhan, because Wuhan girls have bad tempers and are very aggressive. Many families in Wuhan are decided by women, and my girlfriend often stresses that we are not equal, " Ge said.

Yanjiao is separated from Beijing by a river, but it is not the river but the checkpoint on the river that separates them. Checkpoints play an extremely important role in the lives of Yanjiao people.

One day in late February, Ge Yulu was told that, as a Wuhan native whose ID card began with 42, he would have to hand in his residence card and would not be allowed to enter the community again, six months after his last visit to Wuhan. At the same time, he had bought a ticket to Thailand, with this 42 ID card, through the Beijing checkpoint.

A few days ago, I had a chat with Ge Yulu, who was already in Bangkok. He told me the story of a man from Wuhan who had come to Beijing twice.

···············

❶

Someone asked me where I lived,

I said I live around the capital

One night in late October 2019, I set off from my home in Yanjiao, with an electric fan in one hand and a blower in the other, to blow a letter to my girlfriend at her home in Mudanyuan, North Third Ring Road. It's her birthday.

Actually, I've been preparing since the night of the 15th. I was planning to leave in the middle of the night. I was going to deliver the letter to my girlfriend at noon on the 16th to celebrate her birthday. As it turned out, I was so optimistic about the difficulty that I passed through the Beijing checkpoint at daybreak on the 16th. But my girlfriend loved the idea and wanted me to finish it, so I set off again in about a week.

The original choice of the early morning departure, is to avoid Yanjiao morning peak. But by three o'clock in the morning, there were more cars on the road, and three trucks roared past me, and I felt as if Yanjiao had woken up by snoring and turning over. Yanjiao people get up very early because they have to go to Beijing to work. I heard that in Yanjiao, many parents get up early in the morning to line up their children for the bus, in order to let their children sleep for a while.

I took a lot of pictures when I blew the letter through the checkpoint, because the checkpoint really played a very important role for all the people living in Yanjiao. No matter how the integration of Beijing, Tianjin and Hebei, as long as the checkpoints are not removed, Beijing and Yanjiao will always be separated by a huge gap.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A letter from Ge Yulu to his girlfriend

The direction of the checkpoint into Beijing, often blocking the long motorcade, out of Beijing direction is unimpeded. No one who hasn't spent hours at a checkpoint is qualified to talk about the poignancy of life in Yanjiao, where commuters have a perpetual black hole of time compared to those who live on the other side of the checkpoint.

And when the moment through the checkpoint, the psychological sense of suffocation disappeared, you are suspicious of all the unknown, do not exist, at this time, whether Yanjiao people or Beijingers, are reduced to human, no longer be separated, divided.

In a sense, the checkpoint is also an observation station, a weather vane that perceives Beijing. It's not as immutable as we might think. The equipment status of the checkpoints, the open passages, the intensity of the inspections, change from day to day. Sometimes the Beijing license plates are exempt from inspection, and occasionally the foreign cars are exempt from inspection; sometimes the police need to see the driver's ID card, and sometimes the identity card of the entire vehicle owner. Sometimes the inspection is very strict and complicated, that kind of indisputable, no reason to speak, can only look at the face, look at the direction of the wind, can only wait for the feeling, every Yanjiao people have some experience.

My rent in Yanjiao is 1600 a month, two bedroom one living room, quite cheap, the scenery is also good, downstairs is Chaobai River, across the river is Tongzhou. If such a house were in downtown Beijing, the monthly rent would be in the five figures.

Before moving to Yanjiao, I lived in a village in the city of Beijing. One Time I was surfing the Internet at home, someone knocked on the door to check my id, I said I can't live? He said yes, no problem. And then he left, and pretty soon the landlord said to me, "you can't stay, because you opened the door for the inspector, "and if you ignore him, he thinks the house is empty, so you can stay. ". But how do I know who doesn't knock?

On another occasion, I lugged my suitcase back to the house and found that my place was cordoned off and a black clad security guard stood every ten metres. I'm like, is there a bomb in the building or something. One of the security guards told me that you can't stay, so if there's a problem, let them know. I looked, there are several people sitting around drinking tea playing Mahjong, I told them, I just got off the plane, home has not yet come back, can give a break for two days. They said, "don't tell me. You found a new house in time. ".

After these two experiences, I never want to live in Beijing again. Now when people ask me where I live, I will say I live "around Beijing" , which is a circle around Beijing.

❷

Chaobai River is so narrow,

You'd look more like a Wuhan

Yanjiao is part of Langfang in the administrative territorial entity, but in the prevention and control of the epidemic, reference is Beijing's standard, access to residential areas need a pass. The first time I got a pass was around February 7, when I saw a notice at the gate of the community saying that everyone must get a pass. It also said that we should learn the prevention and control of Wuhan, which means that the prevention and control has been upgraded.

When I went to apply for a certificate, I didn't have any problems. Only when I registered my hometown, the aunts in the neighborhood committee saw that I had written "Hubei Wuhan. " They were all taken aback. After I finished writing, they collectively stepped back half a step, it was a very dramatic scene. Aunt asked me, you are Hubei Wuhan, Ah, you spent years here? I mean, I heard about the outbreak years ago, and I never went back.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The letter to my girlfriend arrived at the checkpoint

On the 27th, I got a phone call from the property owner, who said, "I'm sorry, but you have to give back your pass, because you're from Hubei Province, and it starts with 42. ". I said why do you want me to return, he said we have no way, specific you can consult with the Neighborhood Committee.

I called the Neighborhood Committee, I said the property informed me, because my identity card is 42 beginning, the pass must be withdrawn, I can not leave the community, there is this? The residents'committee said that there is indeed such a thing, just under the notice conveyed the spirit of the Beijing side of the meeting, said that after all ID card 42 beginning, are not allowed to enter and leave the community.

I was just about to explain that I had no history of travel to Hubei when he cut me off. He said, this is a one size fits all, just admit it. I was speechless, because he was having a good time too, unlike some of the staff, who were kind of taking their time.

But I had already bought a plane ticket to Thailand, so I asked him if I wouldn't come back if I went out of the neighborhood. He said, even if you out of the community, also can not enter Beijing, the checkpoint to see the beginning of the 42 ID card will not be released. Hearing this, I quickly asked in the group of Hitchhikers, the first 42 ID card can pass the checkpoint. Basically, all I got from the driver was, "forget it. You can't leave. It's over. ".

I was going to return the ticket, but the hotel asked me to provide a certificate that I could not go because of Beijing's prevention and control policy. I thought, this is interesting. Who's going to provide you with the documents? It's a tacit agreement.

So I called the 12345 and asked if there was a policy that said no one with a 42 id was allowed in Beijing. The response from the other side was also quick, saying that they had not heard of such a document so far, and they would look into it as soon as possible and give me a reply. I said I was in a hurry to get out of here, in case I got stopped at the checkpoint. He said in your case, there's no problem getting through the checkpoint, and if you get into trouble at the checkpoint, you can call back.

At that time, I felt that my ticket could not be refunded. I planned to ride my electric bike into Beijing the next day to try and see if I could be stopped. I also have a small video camera that I want to record the process. But it just so happens that since I was a graduate student at the China Central Academy of Fine Arts, I had an ID card with a Beijing address, and then because of a series of events, I didn't go through the formal process of withdrawing my Hukou the year I graduated, although my Hukou was also repatriated, this Beijing Address ID card has not been withdrawn. So now I have two ids, and both of them are valid.

That day I rode an electric bicycle to the gate of the community. The volunteer who was responsible for checking the ID card did not know 42. He took a look at the Beijing address on my ID card and let me out. When I arrived at the checkpoint, the police took my ID card and scanned it. I was allowed to enter Beijing. I was in a daze. I couldn't believe it. I bought some food in Tongzhou and went back to Yanjiao.

Then I received a phone call from the neighborhood committee, said that the government is currently refining the policy, two days will be issued a special pass for Hubei People.

But I still do not trust, I think the policy changes from time to time, a not stopped does not mean anything. Yanjiao is separated from Beijing only by Chaobai River, and the checkpoint is a bridge over Chaobai River. At first I thought I'd swim across the Chaobai River if I had to. Because Hubei is the province of a thousand lakes, Wuhan people can swim, water is very good, can not swim we call him "dry duck" . Ever since I was a kid, my dad used to tell me that he swam the Yangtze River, the East Lake, and so did my high school teacher. It was kind of like a rite of passage for a primitive tribe, only after swimming across the Yangtze River and across the East L. , you are a brave and resourceful, mental maturity, physical quality of the Wuhan people, qualified to call themselves Wuhan People. I think Chaobai River is so narrow that you'd look like a Hubei.

At first, I wanted to find a basin from home, to simplify the luggage, put it in the basin, Drag Basin to swim. But there was a practical problem. There was still ice on the river, and the water temperature must have been close to zero. So I looked up some matters related to winter swimming on the Internet, such as how much water I could swim in and how long I could only swim in, after that, you could go into shock or even die. I also studied the map and selected the narrowest stretch of the Chaobai River River, which is about 160 meters wide. After a comprehensive evaluation, I found it a little difficult to drag my luggage through the freezing water.

Then I thought, can find an hour to take a bath in the kind of large tub, with people and luggage row past. But they don't sell them in supermarkets or in JD.com. So I took the opportunity to search the Kayak in jd.com, and found that there was indeed a Kayak that could be delivered the next day, and could bear nearly 200 kilograms. My luggage and I were all right on it, so I quickly placed the order and gave it a name, it's called "the 42 boats. ".

Until the day I set off for the airport (March 2) , I also did not wait for the residents of Hubei promised exclusive pass. My flight was at five o'clock in the afternoon, and I left early in the morning, thinking that if I got stopped at the checkpoint, I would follow my backup plan and go home to get my Kayak.

I hitchhiked to the checkpoint, and sure enough, the policy tightened. I handed my ID card to the police in the car, and as soon as he brushed it, the alarm started screaming, and I thought, "this is it. ". Then the police pulled me out of the car and the paramedics handed me a Mercury-in-glass thermometer, tucked under my arm, to take my temperature.

I said, "comrade policeman, I'm going on a plane. " Why did you stop me. He said, "who stopped you? We're doing research. ". And then he asked me where I was going on the plane, and I said Thailand. He took a picture of my ticket and everything, and he let me go. Once again, I was confused. I had bought my Kayak for nothing.

❸

Wuhan is the past of Beijing,

Beijing is the future of Wuhan

In 2015, I did a piece called East Lake Station. I took down the stop sign for the Beijing 913 bus station in East L. and installed it in the middle of East L. .

In Beijing, the name of East L. refers to a place called the East L. Canal, near Wangjing North River Park, a little further north is laiguangying. There's no water. It's a high-rise. I guess it used to be a lake, and then it was filled in.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
East Lake, Beijing

I have a vague sense that East L. in Beijing may be the future of Wuhan and East L. . For Wuhan, Beijing is the future; for Beijing, Wuhan is a stage of urban development that it has experienced. The development of a city is also a process in which its geographical environment is constantly changing and its space is constantly being eaten away.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ge Yulu's "East Lake station"

The process of Wuhan's urbanization is also the process of Wuhan's flavor being erased little by little. My family lives on south central road, near the long distance passenger terminal, not far from Wuchang Railway Station. According to our old Wuhan Standard, this already belongs to the quite partial place. When I was a kid, there were a lot of street food stalls and pushcarts downstairs. I would sit down in one of the stalls. These places are a bit messy by today's standards, because many people eat with their shirts off, like a gangster, and some people have dragons tattooed on their bodies, and they talk very loudly, and sometimes they fight and curse, it's got everything.

There is a famous street in Hankou called Jiqing Street, because the whole street is full of Hawker stalls, the road is covered with oil, if you wear a pair of rubber-soled shoes, walking on it will be sticky. Jiqing street is filled with people who eat all the year round, and buskers will put on performances, some of them playing and singing, some of them performing crosstalk. There's no stage, there's no theater, there's no dining room. It's called "immersive theater. " You're eating, and someone jumps out and plays at your table.

Later, Jiqing street rebuilt a lot of western-style buildings, especially foreign style, but the street culture has disappeared. It's never gonNA come back. Now go to Jiqing Street, even feel a bit cold, the style of the street is also in the soil and the ocean between the uncertainty, the beautiful house inside to buy a hot dry noodles, beef powder next door is the Ice Queen, it does not match.

I can not say that I am absolutely negative about urban renewal, but I am very skeptical. I am one of the generation that grew up with the urban renewal of Wuhan. As soon as I graduated from Primary School, I moved to a new campus. As soon as I graduated from junior high school, I moved to a new campus. Half of my senior high school years were spent in a new campus. As soon as I entered college, to the new campus just completed, the campus road has not yet been repaired, a dirt road in the middle of a house, is our dormitory.

When I read undergraduate course, it is the climax of Wuhan Demolition and construction. From the early 1990s when I was born to the present, the biggest change in Wuhan has been the collapse of public space, which may seem abstract, but the way people use public space and its possibilities are gradually being disciplined and compressed.

When I was a child, I lived in my grandparents'house. In the summer, it was too hot to buy air conditioning. At night, we moved our beds onto the street. Everyone in the family went out into the street, fanning themselves, and sat down together to talk. We got tired of chatting, so we all slept together in the street. Today I sleep next to the next-door neighbor, tomorrow is downstairs who, the day after tomorrow and another person. Our kids were so happy because the bed was so close to the bed that they could hop from one end of the street to the other without touching their feet.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
When Ge Yulu was a child, "he was bald when he was so young. "

Today, of course, everyone has air conditioning, the streets are getting wider and wider, and more importantly, it has changed from a pedestrian street to a car street, and now I go back to my grandparents'street and find it has become a parking lot.

Wuhan has been striving to become a spiritual city since then. Anything that does not conform to the norms of spiritual civilization will be banned, such as spitting, running traffic lights, and wearing pajamas on the street. In the past, for Wuhan people, it was normal for men to wear shorts and women to wear pyjamas, and no one would think it was immoral or play Hooligan. People were talking calmly and swinging their fans. I think people were very civilized at that time.

Now every time I go back to Wuhan, just arrived a few days, will be a little floating feeling. I haven't changed, Wuhan has. But after a while, we will find that the spirit of Wuhan has always been there, but hidden in the dramatic changes in the city landscape.

Wuhan has always been in my blood, I speak with a Wuhan accent, sometimes by Beijing friends ridicule, I will laugh, and very proud and proud. Wuhan taught me the "not convinced week" (Wuhan dialect in the meaning of not believe in evil) , will let me life-long use.
